narrative.baseline_conditions: Corn is planted in a fall strip-till program with NH3 in the strip.  Starter fertilizer containing N, S. & Zn.  Sidedressed 28%N  P & K are applied to corn stalks prior to cereal rye drilled as a cover crop.  Cover crop prior to corn has been spring oats, radish, rape and rye.  Changed to spring oats, radish, rape, and winter barley in fall of 2020.  P & K were added to corn strip in fall of 2020

fields.description: Tiled east and west on 75 ft. centers with drainage control structures on east side. Long term no-till (since 1988) and cover crops (since 2012)  Prevent plant on corn 2019  30 ft. lane on North with 8 ft. waterway on east

Gradual slope south to north, east end has an HEL designation.  Tilled south to north and west to east.  !00 ft. filter strip on the NE side of field next to drainage ditch  No-till (since 1988) and cover crops (since 2012)

narrative.baseline_conditions: This field is a corn-soybean rotation for a long time.  It has been strip till corn (with deep-banding of P in the strips and no-till beans) and no-till soybean for 10+ years.  Following corn, Steve has grown cereal rye as a cover crop and, since 2017, soybeans have been followed with a winter barley cover crop (so in fall 2017 and fall 2019).  In 2018, Steve used a split N application using 100 lbs of fall-applied anhydrous ammonia plus MAP (as deep-banded P, as described above).  In 2020, Steve moved to no-fall-N and 20 gall 32% UAN with planter (2x2 application) and balance of N is sidedressed as anhydrous ammonia.

narrative.baseline_conditions: Conventional Tillage has been practiced for a number of years.  Broadcast fertilizer applicatiions were the traditional method of application, however we have recently moved to a variable rate application to intensify nutrient management and to save money.
